The [[Russia national football team|Russian]] squad was made up entirely of players from the country's domestic league. [[English football league system|England]]'s squad had only one player employed by a non-domestic club: [[Fraser Forster]] was employed in [[Scottish Professional Football League|Scotland]]; although it was also part of the United Kingdom, they had a separate national federation and league system from England. The [[Belgium national football team|Belgian]] squad had the most players from a single foreign federation, with twelve players employed in [[English football league system|England]], although one of these, [[Thibaut Courtois]], was only on loan to [[Premier League|English]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] prior to the tournament. Of the countries not represented by a national team at the World Cup, [[Turkish football league system|Turkey's league]] provided the most squad members.

Only [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]'s squad was made up entirely of players employed by overseas clubs, although one player on that squad, [[Sebastián Coates]], played for a domestic club immediately before the World Cup, doing so while on loan from [[Premier League|English]] club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. Three squads had only one domestic-based player ([[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]).

